included.description:
Our application will facilitate a group of people living in clusters (e.g. the same neighborhood, or a group of roommates) to shop on behalf of each other to save time, fuel, and energy. Users can save shopping lists, share a shopping list with a person who is shopping or will go shopping in the near future. As a passive shopper or active shopper, the user can see all of the shared lists - from his group and individually. Active shoppers can easily choose whom to shop for and whom to reject. Passive shoppers can request volunteered active shoppers to take them along for shopping as well. Payment can be made by passive shoppers instantaneously to active shoppers or to the store for the active shopper to carry the shopped items back. This application can be installed and worked on any smartphone (both android and apple), can be accessed by any web browser, and can be operated effortlessly by any user. We hope the principles of weak ties and peer recognition to be an encouragement factor for the use of the âO-Shopâ app.
O-Shop will facilitate improvement in social networking and increases in social capital by boosting user communication. Awareness of active shoppers and each otherâs activities in a group will enhance social translucence in a community

included.name: Analysis of Generational Perceptions on Proscriptive Cellphone Usage Norms in Social Spaces.
included.publisher: Sociology Department at University of Washington
included.description:
Are there generational differences in perceptions of proscriptive norms surrounding how individuals should use mobile phones in social spaces? In this ethnographic study, I interviewed 20 subjects in Seattle: ten people from the Baby Boomer generation and ten people from the Millennial generation. The Baby Boomers considered strangersâ cellphone use behavior in public inappropriate and family membersâ cellphone use as acceptable, whereas Millennials disregarded strangersâ cellphone use in public but recognized that cellphone use on dates was offensive.
My honors thesis was presented in the Sociology Symposium and the Undergraduate Research Symposium at the University of Washington.
